We're counting on you to protect the religious liberty of people with disabilities, as children and as adults. Thank you.
I tell educators to tell parents that they no longer need to fear losing their children in this way. Please make sure that stays true.
Because of inclusive education and HCBS infrastructure, that's no longer the case. We're keeping our communities, now.
You are old enough to remember when children with disabilities almost all disappeared into institutions as they grew up.
One thing I tell Jewish early childhood programs is that parents are often scared that their child's disability means they'll disappear.
I work for @ MatanInc. We work to make sure Jewish children with disabilities have access to Jewish education within their communities.
HCBS infrastructure is what makes it possible for disabled Americans to practice their religion. Without HCBS, there's no religious liberty.
Even when people in nursing homes are able to go to churches and synagogues, they generally have a very narrow range of options.
Please @ SenatorCardin try to push through the # Yes2SAFE act, HR 113 bless you you sirpic.twitter.com/l1Ly9eNCnG
For instance, while Catholics in nursing homes have the legal right to help accessing sacraments, this often falls by the wayside.
Even very basic observance can become a problem in institutions, for people of all faiths.
It's very hard for someone to stay connected to a community if they are forced to wait for available nursing home staff to take them places.
Even under ideal circumstances, nursing home placement is isolating — people are not able to come and go as they please.
For many Jews, religious community requires living within walking distance of a synagogue. This is rarely possible in an institution.
Institutional placements also cut people off from their communities. Eg: There may be no available nursing homes near a Jewish community.
Even with no malicious intent, the structure of institutional placements prevents people from practicing their religion.
In institutional placements, other people control what you eat, when you get up and go to bed, where you're allowed to go, & everything else
In order to have religious freedom, people need control over their own lives. This is only possible with HCBS services.
This is a problem for a number of reasons — one reason I haven't seen discussed much is the devastating impact on religious liberty.
HCBS is more cost-effective in the long term, but it requires initial investment. Per capita caps and other cuts prevent this investment.
HCBS services also make it possible for people to work — institutions and nursing home placements needlessly prevent people from working.
HCBS services keep people out of institutions, and support them in living wherever and however they choose to live.
People with disabilities rely on Home and Community Based Services provided by Medicaid in order to have control over their lives.
